where the primed sum runs over nearest-neighbor sites.
Since we start with a disordered sample, all possible nearest-neighbor configurations, including $| {\uparrow}; {\uparrow} {\rangle}$, $| {\downarrow}; {\downarrow} {\rangle}$, and $| {\downarrow}{\uparrow}; 0 {\rangle}$ will be present. The jump operators, therefore, need to convert the latter into those with the local antiferromagnetic order, $| {\uparrow}; {\downarrow} {\rangle}$. 

We choose the jump operators to be as follows:
\begin{eqnarray}
\hat{j}^{(1)}_{ij, {\uparrow}} &=& \sqrt{\gamma_1} | {\downarrow}{\uparrow}; 0 {\rangle\langle} {\uparrow}; {\uparrow} | , \qquad \hat{j}^{(2)}_{ij, {\uparrow}} = \left( \hat{j}^{(1)}_{ij, {\uparrow}} \right){^\dagger}, \\
\hat{j}^{(1)}_{ij, {\downarrow}} &=& \sqrt{\gamma_1} | {\downarrow}{\uparrow}; 0 {\rangle\langle} {\downarrow}; {\downarrow} | , \qquad \hat{j}^{(2)}_{ij, {\downarrow}} = \left( \hat{j}^{(1)}_{ij, {\downarrow}} \right){^\dagger}, \\
\hat{j}^{(3)}_{ij} &=& \sqrt{\gamma_2} | {\downarrow}; {\uparrow} {\rangle\langle} 0; {\downarrow}{\uparrow} |.
\end{eqnarray}

The two labels of $\vert \dots \rangle$ and $\langle \dots \vert$ refer to the nearest-neighbor sites $i$ and $j$, while $\gamma_1$, $\gamma_2$ are the dissipation rates. 
Their combined action, schematically shown in Fig.~\ref{fig1}(a), leads to turning the configurations, $| {\uparrow}; {\uparrow} {\rangle}$, $| {\downarrow}; {\downarrow} {\rangle}$, and $|{\uparrow}{\downarrow}; 0{\rangle}$, into those with the AF order, $| {\uparrow}; {\downarrow} {\rangle}$. 
We note that the jump operators $\hat{j}^{(3)}_{ij}$ break the SU(2) symmetry, as the down-spin atom becomes more mobile. This, however, does not constitute a limitation of our scheme. Moreover, it is  possible to reestablish the symmetry by using additional auxiliary states to induce hopping of the $|{\uparrow}{\rangle}$-state atom away from the double-occupancy configuration.

As we discuss in the following section, such  choice of the jump operators is straightforward to realize in experiment using incoherent laser scattering.

